<h2>Off-Page SEO and AI Search Visibility</h2>
<p>Off-page signals now affect more than Google rankings. They influence whether AI search engines cite your content.</p>
<p>Sites with 32,000+ referring domains are 3.5 times more likely to get cited by ChatGPT (<a href="https://seranking.com/blog/seo-statistics/">SE Ranking</a>). Perplexity, Google AI Overviews, and Gemini also favor sources with strong authority signals when selecting citations.</p>
<h3>How Off-Page SEO Feeds AI Citations</h3>
<p>AI search engines evaluate source credibility before citing. The signals they use overlap heavily with traditional off-page SEO:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Backlink profile strength</strong> signals domain authority to AI models</li>
<li><strong>Brand mentions</strong> across trusted sites build entity recognition</li>
<li><strong>Reviews and ratings</strong> contribute to trustworthiness evaluation</li>
<li><strong>Co-citations</strong> (being mentioned alongside authoritative sources) build topical association</li>
</ul>
<h3>The Co-Citation Strategy</h3>
<p>Co-citation means being mentioned in the same context as established authorities. If your brand appears alongside HubSpot, Ahrefs, and Moz in industry discussions, AI models associate your brand with that level of authority.</p>
<p>Build co-citations by:
- Contributing expert quotes to roundup posts
- Appearing on industry podcasts
- Getting featured in "best of" lists alongside known brands
- Publishing research that authoritative sources reference</p>
